Case Study 1: Birth Weight

Moriah Taylor, Faraz Yashar, AJ Eckmann, Audreya Metz, Naya Chen

9/4/2019

Exploratory Analysis and Transformations

A normal pregnancy ranges from 38 to 42 weeks. (Source: https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/002367.htm)

We note a gestational age nearly double that time at 80. We will remove the entry with that value since we consider it a clerical error.

First we begin by inspecting the relationships between birth weight gestational age, maternal age, pairty, and plurality.

We note that gestational age has a decent amount of curvature which might be helped with a quadratic term. This however would affect interpretability.

Maternal age seems to have little effect outside of the tails (e.g. greater than 45 years of age). Introduction of a nonlinearity would appear helpful here. Parity on birth weight seems to have a small effect. Plurality has a very pronounced effect.

We now inspect the relationship of weight with race, hispanic status, year of birth and county.

Note the horizontal bar plotted is the average birthweight.

Inspecting race, certain race covariates appear to deviate signficantly from the mean, suggesting that this is a covariate of interest. Reading trough the literature, it appears that in another study of gestational variation published in the International Journal of Epidemiology entitled “Does gestation vary by ethnic group? A London-based study of over 122,000 pregnancies with spontaneous onset of labour” (https://academic.oup.com/ije/article/33/1/107/668109) categorization of european, african, and asian ancestry suffices.

MRACER 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8
Freq 83225 415716 172250 9991 3326 575 92 2108 23086

With this as prior knowledge, we’ll consider grouping together all of the racial categories of asian ancestry to simplify interpreation.

Due to their small size, the granular subsets of hispanic ethnicity may not be very informative. Investigating the covariate directly, we note the majority reported as not hispanic.

MHISP C M N O P S U
Freq 1576 63647 603574 6367 8140 26717 348

As such, we will consider a transformation to turn hispanic ethnicity into a binary covariate.

Certain counties appear to have significant deviation from the mean. Since county is a proxy for socioeconomic status, it would be worthwhile to link counties through census data to useful socioeconomic indicator such as median income. This would reduce the number of covariates significantly. This would require the addition of another dataset to our analysis, so for the purpose of this study we will choose to ignore the CORES variable.

Inspecting year of bith more closely, we see little variation in any of the covariates year over year.

As such, we believe that there is not a significant time-related trend and that year of birth is potentially not a covariate of interest.

We now inspect the smoking variables.

Note in most cases we observe an initial drop from zero followed by wild fluctuations as the number of cigarettes smoked per day increases. The vast majority of mothers are non smokers throughout each phase of pregnancy.

  • 86.8% of women don’t smoke before pregancy.
  • 90.5% of women don’t smoke during the first trimester.
  • 92% of women don’t smoke during the second trimester.
  • 92.4% of women don’t smoke during the last trimester.

In addition, a correlation matrix revealed heavy correlations between all of the smoking variables.

This lead us to beleive that binarizing each of the smoking covariates or combining them into a single covariate would make sense.

Investigating the models above, we see that log transforming the outcome improves fit greatly, however this is clearly a result of overfitting as the RMS errors are the highest for those transformations. Binarization increased performance broadly. Introducing quadratic terms did nothing. Of the models with the lowest RMSE (within 0.1 from the smallest), we see that the model which binarizes the smoking variables, combines the races as mentioned prior, and drops the hispanic term (bsmokes_bpar_crace_dhisp) performs extremely well when compared against the other models of similar performance. In our view, this model has the optimal blend of simplicity, interpretability and performance.

Now that we have selected our covariates, we’ll build our final OLS model and compare it against a robust regression.
